## Conclusion and Opinion

The exodus of healthcare workers is driven by a confluence of factors, with burnout and poor management at the forefront. While compensation and benefits are important, they are insufficient alone to stem the tide of departures. The pandemic has acted as a catalyst, exposing and intensifying pre-existing systemic issues such as inadequate staffing, lack of career development, and poor organizational culture.

To address this crisis, healthcare organizations must adopt a holistic approach that prioritizes mental health support, improves management practices, optimizes workload and scheduling, and invests in career advancement opportunities. Ignoring these factors risks further attrition, jeopardizing patient care and the sustainability of healthcare systems.

Investing in workforce well-being is not merely an expense but a strategic imperative with substantial returns in retention, quality of care, and financial stability. Leadership must demonstrate empathy and responsiveness to the needs of healthcare workers, fostering an environment where they feel valued, supported, and motivated to continue their vital work.

